text.tspan: Wealth
Management
DBS

- Moving from physical to “Phygital” to redefine client experience: arming RMs with data to re-define client experience; sharing curated, actionable insights, aligned to client risk-profiles; building digital platforms with AI/ML- backed capabilities; updating portfolios in real-time, with 24/7 transaction capabilities.

- Place data and AI/ML at the core of client management: curating deep data insights to develop bespoke recommendations, with 16,000+ curated data points and needs/interests predictions for next best nudges and next best conversation.

- Use AI-assisted hyper personalized nudges, sent directly to clients at the right time to allow “ Self-directed Execution”, creating “awareness” of market events impacting clients’ holding and portfolio risk appetite.
- Aim to redefine private banking for a new era – persoanlised, sophisticated and AI-powered solutioning.

- In 2023/4 Digital efforts include leveraging data and AI/ ML to provide relationship managers with insights to better engage their customers, and investments in API and core processing capabilities to seize opportunities in low-value real-time payments, supply chain financing and treasury customer solutions, advanced our goal
of becoming the primary bank for an increasing number of wealth and business clients.
This includes the internal launch of “DBS-GPT,” an employee-facing version of ChatGPT, which assists staff with content generation, summarization, and querying the organization’s knowledge base.

- Economic Impact: DBS projects that its AI initiatives will generate over SGD 1 billion in economic value by 2025, building on the SGD 750 million achieved in 2024; This value is derived from deploying more than 1,500 AI models across over 370 use cases, spanning customer-facing businesses, support functions, and risk
management.
-CEO has challenged teams to develop both vertical and horizontal use cases for generative AI to harness efficiencies, capacity release, and better top-line growth

- In December 2024, DBS partnered with Enterprise Singapore and the Infocomm Media Development Authority (IMDA) to promote AI adoption among SMEs in Singapore, planning to reach 50,000 SMEs over two years
HSBC
- Developing digital capabilities for wealth management: launched >650 digital features since 2020, from digital self-execution to hybrid client journeys.
- Provide intelligent support and guidance: anytime support from Intelligent Wealth Assistant chatbot. Access to dedicated staff via RM Chat. Exchanged >400k messages with our clients via GPB Chat.
- Prism Advisory: in partnership with Blackrock Aladdin, HSBC launched Prism Advisory which is a holistic portfolio-based investment service that combine expert guidance and data driven insights.

- Global Private Banking launched AI-driven investment strategy, AIGO8, an AI-driven multi-asset index, which provides global diversification with opportunistic exposure to 18 assets spanning global equities, fixed income, inflation sensitive assets and cash.

- At 54%, more than half of WPB customers were mobile active, an increase of 6 percentage points from 2022. Furthermore,a total of 75% of WPB’s international customer accounts were opened digitally in 2023, an increase of 30 percentage points from 2022

- At present, HSBC employ Al in areas such as fraud detection and transaction monitoring. They also launched Al Markets, a digital service that utilises natural language processing to enrich the way investors interact with global markets. Additionally, they are in the process of piloting numerous generative Al use cases in areas like
developer augmentation, creative content generation and knowledge management, and have identified hundreds more potential opportunities.

HSBC is 'undergoing a comprehensive transformation of its operations, modernizing infrastructure, and investing in technology such as AI, generative AI, data, and analytics to enhance customer experience and drive operational excellence' (4Q24 earnings).
-Deployed coding assistants to over 20,000 engineers, supporting approximately 15% efficiency in time spent coding
-Using generative AI in 5 Corporate and Investment Banking (CIB) markets to support credit analysis write-ups
Mizuho
-In branch operations, AI is utilized to enhance call center and chatbot functions that enable customers to access services remotely.
- In Global Markets business, the company is strengthening sales dashboards using AI analysis to provide solutions for customers.
Banking operations integrating investment and ALM are conducted using high-frequency data and AI.
- In June 2023, Mizuho and Fujitsu announced the start of joint trials using generative AI to enhance product quality in Mizuho’s system development and maintenance phases.
- In staff training operations, Mizuho has created a digital learning platform and is building shared platforms to boost employee productivity using ChatGPT.

- In September 2024, Mizuho Financial Group announced it was buying a stake in AI developer Sakana AI. The firm commented that Sakana AI’s technology would allow it to surpass limitations on AI use and deliver radical efficiency gains with new added value.

--Mizuho FG developed a comprehensive AI strategy focused on operational efficiency, customer experience enhancement, innovation, responsible AI implementation, and workforce transformation. While promoting the use of DX in administrative and clerical work, we understand that the use of AI is also being considered for

sales operations (e.g., asset management consultations). As a specific initiative, in Aug 2024, it launched a next-generation contact center utilizing AI for individual businesses, which analyzes customer interview content in real time and automatically predicts and proposes products and services that meet customer needs to

operators. According to the company's financial results for F3/25 1H, the time required to resolve customer issues via chat was reduced by approximately 10%. In addition, it is introducing AIOCR as part of our operational reforms.
OCBC

- The application of AI, combined with big data allows bank to offer clients personalized investment insights, market updates, and thematic content, ensuring the clients remain informed and can capitalize on potential opportunities.

- OCBC Securities customers in Singapore are able to access stock recommendations online powered by AI. The AI bots will also suggest stocks that customers should pay attention to on a given day. the bank will also be rolling out hyper-personalised tips based on each customer’s profile. These will be sent out via e-mail for
those who are on the OCBC Securities mailing list, and can also be accessed through the iOCBC app.

- Beyond directly serving customers, banks have also found ways to use AI to power back-end functions to increase productivity and accuracy. For example, OCBC is progressively rolling out OCBC GPT, based off ChatGPT, a natural language processing tool driven by AI technology.
- Aim to capture wealth flows by leveraging digital strengths

- OCBC Securities has launched A.I. Oscar (OCBC Securities’ Customer Artificial-Intelligence Radar), Singapore’s first artificial intelligence (AI)-powered stock-picker tool, to triple its base of active Singapore young investors. A.I. Oscar is able to predict stock price movements and generate hyper-personalised stock ideas. A.I.
Oscar’s coverage include Singapore, Hong Kong and United States markets.
-In November 2024, OCBC formed a strategic partnership with Ant International to enhance cross-border fund settlements.

-In 2024, OCBC transitioned its AI strategy from experimentation to operational use, embedding AI into daily operations for tasks ranging from personalizing credit card deals to detecting fraud.1 The bank has set ambitious goals for AI integration across its business operations.
-OCBC aims for 75% of all customer service requests to be AI-assisted.
-The bank anticipates a 20% increase in staff productivity by 2027, with every employee benefiting from AI support.
SMFG

- SMFG aims to build a business infrastructure that harnesses digitalization. In order to provide high-value-added solutions, it is developing resources through digital applications that use data and AI, and allocating these resources to the creation of proposals for large and small clients that require high levels of specialization.
- The company is working to improve productivity by strengthening it infrastructure. it is using generative AI to collate and analyze data and prepare relevant materials

- In July 2024, SMFG announced a capital tie-up with Fintech firm Money Forward. Under the Alliance, the companies will consider jointly releasing a service which provides AI-powered personalized proposals for improving money habits based on analyses of personal finances and assets as well as the use of various financial
services.
- In September 2024, SMBC bought a stake in AI developer Sakana AI alongside other Japanese financial institutions (including other megabanks).

--Of the ¥800bn IT investment budget for the current medium-term management plan (ending in F3/26), ¥240bn will be allocated to growth investments. Within this, the company has announced that it will set an additional investment budget of ¥50bn, including the next medium-term management plan, with the aim of creating new

businesses that effectively utilize generative AI. In F3/25 1H the company announced its intention to develop AI as a partner for humans in core banking operations such as lending and asset management proposals, with a focus on data analysis, customer demand forecasting, and proposal models utilizing avatars.

-SMFG is actively pursuing AI initiatives, including the development of an "AI-CEO" and an "AI Supervisor" to support bank employees. The company has also established an AI solutions business in Singapore as part of its international AI strategy. The company aims to establish itself as an "AI-advanced bank" and plans to
fundamentally transform its core business through the use of generative AI technologies.
Standard
Chartered

- CPBB is delivering a single Wealth platform to scale across their footprint and client continuum by replicating standard components across markets and segments. It also provides hybrid RM assisted journey.
- Secured client communication: myRM for investment transaction authorization;

- Digital advisory: myWealth Direct enables personalized investment ideas delivered directly to clients and myWealth Advisor is a advanced advisory tool for RM/IAs with personalized portfolio construction.

- State of art trading infrastructure: SC Online Equities provides instant access to 12 exchanges, Wealth FX Online trading platform has 28 currencies; FI Mobile for fixed income trading platform; Online Mutual Funds platform supporting > 80% of transaction.

- In 2023, more than 20 new digital wealth capabilities were launched, including client DIY Wealth Lending for Funds in Hong Kong and theUAE and MyInsure in India where relationship managers can leverage a digital tool to perform comprehensive insurance needs analysis and portfolio reviews for clients.

- For CPBB, Standard Chartered aims to harpen on-boarding and engagement capabilities through digital sales and marketing, advanced analytic capabilities and straight-through self-service to improve client experience and efficiency
-In December 2024, Mohammed Rahim was appointed Group Chief Data Officer, tasked with steering the bank's data initiatives to support its AI ambitions.

-Standard Chartered is committed to "leveraging the benefits of augmented AI while managing these risks" as a core part of their business model. The bank noted a large increase in the use of AI in fraud, scams, and spreading misinformation. (1H25 report)
-The bank is currently finalizing a formal AI strategy, expected to be presented to its board in mid-2025, focusing on aligning AI initiatives with broader business goals.

-In June 2025, Yusuf Demiral was appointed to the newly created role of Global Head, Wealth and Retail Banking Data, Analytics and AI, based in Singapore, to lead the AI strategy across the client journey.

-Deployed an AI-enabled "Talent Marketplace" to match internal skills with project needs; Rolled out SC GPT, an internal large language model similar to ChatGPT, to 70,000 employees across 41 markets, which has handled over 150,000 prompts; Exploring AI to improve searches within their extensive Knowledge Management
System.
-In August 2025, Standard Chartered announced a significant AI collaboration with Ant International.
UOB

- Wealth customer acquisition powered by AI/ML models, to identify affluent customers and engage and upgrade them to wealth management platforms to better serve them with a wider range of wealth advisory services and solutions.

- Help customers optimize portfolio through the proprietary Risk-First approach to ensure alignment with the client’s risk profile, life stage and wealth goals. Discussions and decisions are enabled by technology, such as UOB Portfolio Advisory Tools (PAT) and self-serve digital investing platform SimpleInvest. UOB also integrated
deposits and investment data from SGFinDex into PAT.
- 6x response lift on wealth upgrades, 3x lift in wealth cross-sold; 60% response rate to customized electronic digital mail; >90% sales advisory digital adoption of PAT.
- Use AI to identify hidden gems, Client segmentation to create personalised propositions;

Better U Pivot" Programme: This programme was introduced to reskill and upskill existing UOB employees in areas such as risk and compliance, sales, and customer experience, preparing them for roles impacted by digitalization and
automation
- UOB portfolio tool with AI-enabled features to construct client-specific model portfolio and smart trade ideas;

- AI for risk detection and surveillance: Analytics & ML for predictive risk insights and anomaly detection (AML, Suitability, Fraud), Speech-to-Text AI for automation and enhanced review of sales recordings and dynamic analytics platform enables scalability and resource optimisation

-During UOB's 2024 earnings call in February 2025, management discussed how AI could potentially help with credit risk assessment. When asked specifically about whether AI could help with looking at credits, UOB executive Wai Fai Lee responded that while there's no "silver bullet" for credit assessment (as much of it involves

judgment), AI can help with gathering and processing market information that would be more updated. However, he emphasized that prudent credit management still requires close follow-up of cases, especially given how quickly markets can change.

-Partnership with Accenture: UOB has formed a partnership with Accenture to leverage their AI Refinery™ platform and provide employees with access to Accenture's LearnVantage training services to build data and AI fluency across its workforce
